---
import Layout from '@/components/astro/Layout.astro';
import { supabase } from '@/lib/supabase';
import { DollarSign, TrendingUp, AlertCircle, CheckCircle, XCircle, Calculator } from 'lucide-react';

// Fetch some real data to ground our guide
const { data: lobbyists, error } = await supabase
  .from('lobbyists')
  .select('subscription_tier, is_claimed')
  .eq('is_active', true);

const totalLobbyists = lobbyists?.length || 0;
const claimedLobbyists = lobbyists?.filter(l => l.is_claimed).length || 0;

const pageTitle = 'How Much Does a Lobbyist Cost in Texas? 2025 Pricing Guide';
const pageDescription = 'Experienced Texas lobbyist Byron Campbell reveals what you actually pay for lobbying services, what drives costs up or down, and how to know if you\'re getting value. Real numbers, honest guidance.';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: pageTitle,
  description: pageDescription,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: 'Byron Campbell'
  },
  datePublished: '2025-01-06',
  dateModified: '2025-01-06',
};
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} schema={schema}>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-texas-blue-50 via-white to-background py-20 lg:py-28 border-b border-border">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <div class="mb-8">
        <a
          href="/guides"
          class="inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-600 hover:text-texas-blue-700 transition-colors group"
        >
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 mr-2 transition-transform group-hover:-translate-x-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18" />
          </svg>
          Back to all guides
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-texas-blue-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-700 mb-6">
        Pricing Guide
      </div>

      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-bold mb-6 leading-tight tracking-tight">
        How Much Does a Lobbyist Cost in Texas?
      </h1>

      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground mb-10 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        When companies first hire a lobbyist, they often have no idea what's a fair price. Here's what you'll pay, what you're paying for, and how to know if it's worth it.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-6 text-sm text-muted-foreground border-t border-border pt-6">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">By Byron Campbell, Texas Lobbyist</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">12 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 lg:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">

      <!-- Introduction -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Let me share what separates successful lobbying from wasted money: you're not paying a lobbyist for meetings with legislators. You're paying for relationships built over years, strategic positioning before session starts, and access to committee staff who actually draft the amendments.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          If a lobbyist quotes you $12,000 per month and you think "that's expensive for a few Capitol meetings," you're missing the point entirely. The meetings are the easy part. What you're really buying is everything that happens before and after those meetings‚Äîthe text messages at 9 PM when a committee schedule shifts, the quiet conversation with a staffer over coffee, the coalition work that lines up votes before your bill ever gets a hearing.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          So let's talk about what lobbying actually costs, what drives prices up or down, and how to calculate whether you're getting value for your money.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Answer -->
      <section id="quick-answer" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">The Quick Answer</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">What you'll pay</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Most Texas lobbyists charge between <strong>$5,000 and $25,000 per month</strong> on a retainer basis. You'll typically commit to at least one legislative session (5 months), though many contracts run year-round or cover the full 2-year biennium.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
                <div class="text-sm font-medium text-muted-foreground mb-2">Starting Range</div>
                <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-foreground mb-1">$5K‚Äì$10K</div>
                <div class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Per month</div>
                <div class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-3">Solo practitioners, newer lobbyists, or straightforward monitoring work</div>
              </div>
              <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 rounded-lg border-2 border-texas-blue-500 p-6">
                <div class="text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-700 mb-2">Most Common</div>
                <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-texas-blue-700 mb-1">$10K‚Äì$25K</div>
                <div class="text-sm text-texas-blue-700">Per month</div>
                <div class="text-xs text-texas-blue-700 mt-3">Experienced lobbyists with proven track records and strong relationships</div>
              </div>
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
                <div class="text-sm font-medium text-muted-foreground mb-2">Premium Tier</div>
                <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-foreground mb-1">$25K‚Äì$50K+</div>
                <div class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Per month</div>
                <div class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-3">Large firms, former legislators, high-stakes issues requiring top connections</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            For a typical 5-month session engagement (January through May), expect to invest <strong>$25,000 to $125,000+</strong> depending on complexity and experience level. But that monthly retainer? That's just the starting point.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- What You're Actually Paying For -->
      <section id="what-youre-buying" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">What You're Paying For</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">Understanding the value beyond meetings</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            The reality is that lobbying fees feel expensive until you understand what you're getting. You're not paying for someone to shake hands at the Capitol. You're paying for:
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">Years of Relationship Building</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                That lobbyist who texts committee staff on Sunday night when hearing schedules shift? Those relationships took years to build. You're not paying for the text message‚Äîyou're paying for the decade of trust and credibility that makes the staffer respond.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">Strategic Positioning Before Session Starts</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                Effective lobbyists start working 6-12 months before the Legislature convenes. They're meeting with committee staff during the interim, positioning your issue, identifying potential opposition, and building coalitions. By the time session starts, the groundwork is done.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">Access to Decision-Makers You Can't Reach</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                Committee chairs who won't return your calls? Agency officials who ignore your emails? Your lobbyist has direct lines to these people because they've spent years becoming a trusted source of information and insight.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-orange-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">Strategic Expertise That Prevents Costly Mistakes</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                Good lobbyists know when to push and when to back off, which amendments to fight for and which battles to concede. That strategic judgment comes from experience‚Äîand prevents the amateur mistakes that sink bills and waste money.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            When a $75,000 lobbying investment kills a bill that would have cost your business $5 million in compliance costs, that's not expensive. That's a 67x return on investment. The trick is understanding what you're actually buying.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Pricing Models -->
      <section id="pricing-models" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Four Common Pricing Models</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">How lobbyists structure their fees</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Texas lobbyists typically work under one of four fee structures. Each has advantages and drawbacks depending on your needs and budget.
          </p>

          <!-- Monthly Retainer -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-texas-blue-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-4">
                <div class="bg-texas-blue-500 text-white rounded-full p-3 flex-shrink-0 font-bold text-lg">1</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Monthly Retainer (Most Common)</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    You pay a fixed monthly fee for ongoing representation. This is the standard model and what most experienced lobbyists prefer.
                  </p>

                  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
                    <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-700 mb-2">Why Lobbyists Like It:</p>
                      <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-green-800 ml-4">
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Predictable income stream</li>
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Can plan their time effectively</li>
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Not incentivized to drag things out</li>
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Can build long-term strategy</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-700 mb-2">Why You Should Like It:</p>
                      <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-blue-800 ml-4">
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Budget is predictable</li>
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Lobbyist is always available</li>
                        <li>‚Ä¢ No surprise bills</li>
                        <li>‚Ä¢ Relationship building over time</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Typical structure:</strong> $12,000/month during the 5-month session, $5,000/month during the interim = $97,000 annually</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Hourly Rate -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-4">
                <div class="bg-muted text-foreground rounded-full p-3 flex-shrink-0 font-bold text-lg">2</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Hourly Rate (Less Common for Lobbying)</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    You pay for actual time spent, similar to hiring an attorney. More common for consulting work than active lobbying.
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-amber-900">
                      <strong>The bottom line:</strong> Most experienced Texas lobbyists won't work hourly because their value isn't in billable hours‚Äîit's in relationships and strategic judgment that can't be tracked on a timesheet.
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Typical rates if offered:</strong> $200‚Äì$500/hour depending on experience. But expect 10-40 hours per month during session, which adds up faster than a retainer.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Project-Based -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-4">
                <div class="bg-muted text-foreground rounded-full p-3 flex-shrink-0 font-bold text-lg">3</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Project-Based Fee</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    A flat fee for a specific objective like "Get HB 1234 passed" or "Kill the regulatory change targeting our industry."
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 mb-2">
                      <strong>When this works:</strong> Simple, well-defined goals with clear success criteria. Works best for defensive lobbying (killing a bill) rather than offensive work (passing legislation).
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-900">
                      <strong>Why it's tricky:</strong> Legislative work rarely stays within neat boundaries. Scope creep is real‚Äîwhat starts as "monitor one bill" turns into "fight three amendments, coordinate coalition, and testify four times."
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Typical project fee:</strong> $30,000‚Äì$75,000 for a session-long effort on a specific bill or regulatory matter</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Success Fee -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg border-2 border-red-300 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-4">
                <div class="bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full p-3 flex-shrink-0 font-bold text-lg">4</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Success Fee / Contingency (Proceed with Caution)</h3>
                  <p class="text-red-800 mb-4">
                    Payment only if a specific outcome is achieved‚Äîbill passes, regulation is defeated, appropriation is secured.
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-red-100 border border-red-300 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <div class="flex gap-2">
                      <AlertCircle className="h-5 w-5 text-red-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" />
                      <div>
                        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-900 mb-1">Why Most Reputable Lobbyists Refuse This</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-red-800">
                          Legislative outcomes depend on hundreds of factors beyond any lobbyist's control‚Äîcommittee composition, political climate, competing priorities, legislative leadership's agenda. Promising results you can't control is either naive or unethical.
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <p class="text-sm text-red-900">
                    <strong>Be very wary of any lobbyist who guarantees outcomes in exchange for success fees.</strong> The best lobbyists charge for their time, expertise, and relationships‚Äînot for results they can't promise.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Cost Drivers -->
      <section id="cost-drivers" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">What Drives Costs Higher (or Lower)</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">Understanding the pricing factors</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Two lobbyists might quote you wildly different prices for what looks like similar work. Here's what drives those differences:
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-6">
            <!-- Driver 1 -->
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">1. The Lobbyist's Relationships</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                A former legislative staffer who spent five years as chief of staff for the Senate Finance Committee? They command premium rates for tax and budget issues because they know every member of that committee personally and have the committee clerk's cell phone number.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-sm"><strong>Price impact:</strong> Former legislators and senior staff can charge 2-3x what equally talented "outsider" lobbyists charge‚Äîand for budget or appropriations work, they're often worth every penny.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Driver 2 -->
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">2. Issue Complexity and Controversy</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                A simple technical fix to an obscure statute? Relatively cheap. Trying to change tax policy in a way that creates winners and losers across multiple industries? Buckle up.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-sm"><strong>Price impact:</strong> Controversial issues cost 50-100% more because they require more coalition-building, more opposition research, more meetings, more testimony, and more time managing competing interests.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Driver 3 -->
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">3. Scope of Work</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Monitoring one bill is different from tracking 50 bills across multiple committees. Passing a consensus bill supported by both parties is different from defeating legislation with powerful backers.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-sm"><strong>Price impact:</strong> Monitoring work: +$2K-$5K/month. Active advocacy on 5+ bills: +$10K-$20K/month beyond base rates.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Driver 4 -->
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">4. Timing and Urgency</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Hire a lobbyist in August before the January session? Normal pricing. Call in March when your bill is scheduled for a committee hearing next week? Expect premium pricing‚Äîif they even have capacity.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-sm"><strong>Price impact:</strong> Last-minute engagements can cost 25-50% more. The best lobbyists are often fully booked by November for the following session.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Driver 5 -->
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">5. Subject Matter Expertise</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                A lobbyist with 20 years of healthcare policy experience will charge more for healthcare clients than a generalist‚Äîand they'll be significantly more effective because they know the players, the issues, and the history.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-sm"><strong>Price impact:</strong> Deep expertise in high-demand areas (healthcare, energy, tech, finance) can add 20-40% to base rates.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Hidden Costs -->
      <section id="hidden-costs" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Hidden Costs Nobody Tells You About</h2>
          <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">The monthly retainer is just the starting point</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            The mistake I see constantly: business owners budget for the monthly retainer and think that's the total cost. Wrong. That retainer is the foundation, not the ceiling. You need to budget for additional expenses that can easily double your total cost.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
              <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-1">Political Contributions</h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Expect: $5K‚Äì$50K+ per session</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                While lobbyists can't legally require you to donate to campaigns, the reality is that effective lobbying usually involves strategic campaign contributions to key legislators. Budget $500-$2,500 per targeted legislator.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                <p class="text-xs text-amber-900"><strong>Let's be clear:</strong> Your competitors are probably making these contributions. Not participating puts you at a disadvantage, whether we like it or not.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
              <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-1">Coalition and Association Memberships</h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Expect: $5K‚Äì$25K annually</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">
                Your lobbyist will likely recommend joining industry coalitions or trade associations to amplify your voice. These memberships range from a few thousand dollars to $25K+ for major groups‚Äîbut they provide strength in numbers that solo advocacy can't match.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
              <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-1">Research and Economic Studies</h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Expect: $5K‚Äì$20K per study</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">
                For controversial issues, you may need third-party economic impact studies, public opinion polling, or legal analysis to support your position. These aren't optional when legislators need hard data to justify their votes.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border p-6">
              <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-1">Your Own Time and Staff</h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">20-100+ hours of your time</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Good lobbying is a partnership, not outsourcing. You'll spend significant time briefing your lobbyist, reviewing strategy, attending key meetings, testifying at hearings, and coordinating with stakeholders.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                <p class="text-xs text-blue-900"><strong>Plan for it:</strong> If you think hiring a lobbyist means you can forget about Austin, you're going to be disappointed. Your involvement is critical to success.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-yellow-50 border-2 border-yellow-400 rounded-lg p-6">
            <div class="flex gap-3 mb-4">
              <Calculator className="h-6 w-6 text-yellow-700 flex-shrink-0" />
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-yellow-900">Real-World Total Cost Example</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-yellow-900">
